    "reasoning": "The goal is to implement a thermostat controller based on the provided natural language specification and interface.\n\n**Requirements Analysis:**\n1.  **Mode Control:** `mode=1` is Heating Mode; `mode=0` is Cooling Mode.\n2.  **Heating Mode (mode=1):** Heater turns ON if `too_cold=1`. AC must be OFF. Fan turns ON if Heater is ON or `fan_on=1`.\n3.  **Cooling Mode (mode=0):** AC turns ON if `too_hot=1`. Heater must be OFF. Fan turns ON if AC is ON or `fan_on=1`.\n4.  **Fan Control:** Fan turns ON if Heater is ON OR AC is ON OR `fan_on=1`.\n\n**Logic Derivation:**\n*   **Heater:** Active only in heating mode (`mode == 1`) AND when it is too cold (`too_cold == 1`).\n    $$\\text{heater} = \text{mode} \text{ AND } \text{too\\_cold}$$\n*   **Air Conditioner:** Active only in cooling mode (`mode == 0`) AND when it is too hot (`too_hot == 1`).\n    $$\\text{aircon} = (\text{NOT } \text{mode}) \text{ AND } \text{too\\_hot}$$\n*   **Fan:** Active if Heater is ON OR AC is ON OR `fan_on=1`.\n    $$\\text{fan} = \text{heater} \text{ OR } \text{aircon} \text{ OR } \text{fan\\_on}$$\n\n**Implementation Strategy:**\n1.  Use `logic` data types for all inputs, outputs, and internal signals, as required.\n2.  Since all logic is purely combinational based on the current inputs, the implementation will use continuous `assign` statements for simplicity and direct mapping of the derived Boolean equations. No sequential logic or `always` blocks are needed, which adheres to the constraint of avoiding explicit sensitivity lists in `always @(*)` blocks (though `assign` statements bypass this entirely).\n\n**Syntax Error Avoidance Advice:**\n*   Ensure all port declarations match the `module_interface` exactly, including names and types.\n*   Use standard SystemVerilog operators (`&` for AND, `|` for OR, `~` for NOT, `&&` for logical AND, `||` for logical OR) correctly. The derived logic uses simple AND/OR combinations, which is straightforward.\n*   The specification does not require clocking or state machines, so the complexity of sequential logic constraints (like initialization or reset handling) is avoided.\n\n**Refinement on Fan Logic:** The requirement states: 'When the heater or air conditioner are on, also turn on the fan... In addition, the user can also request the fan to turn on (fan_on = 1)'. This translates directly to the derived OR condition: Fan ON if (Heater ON OR AC ON OR fan_on is asserted).",
